{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ὀπίσω</b> [ῐ], <br /> <i>Epic dialect</i> <b>ὀπίσσω</b>, the former rare in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus and only in signification 1 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Aeolic dialect</i> <b>ὐπίσσω</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica “Papyrus fragments” in E. Diehl, 8.9 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]:— <i>adverb</i>: <br /><Level2><b>__I</b></Level2> of Place, <b>backwards,</b> opposed to to πρόσω, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 12.272 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; to προπρηνές,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3.218; ἀνεχάζετο τυτθὸν ὀπίσσω 5.443; ἀ. πολλὸν ὀ. 16.710; πάλιν εἶσιν ὀπίσσω 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.149: in Prose also, τὸ ὀπίσω,\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] <i>contraction</i> τοὐπίσω, τὸ ὀ. φεύγειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.207, compare 8.108; ἄναγε εἰς τοὐπίσω 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 528a, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 4.4, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Fragmenta” 106, etc.; [γνάμ]φθη δ᾽ ὀπίσσω [φάσγα]νον 5th c.BC: Bacchylides Lyricus 12.53 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὰ ὀ. the <b>hinder parts,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" LXX.Joel.2.20; τοῦ προπύλου τὸ ὀ. μέρος “SIG” 756.17 (Athens, 1st c.BC); τὴν ὀ. τοῦ προπύλου στέγην [prev. work]12; ἐκ τοῦ ὀ.\">LXX+1st c.BC+</a>] on the <b>back</b> (of the papyrus), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “BGU” 1002.16 (1st c.BC)\">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]; τἀπίλοιπα ὀ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PTeb.” 58.37 (2nd c.BC). \">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.2</b></Level3> <b>back, back again,</b> of movement, ἀπήνυσαν οἴκαδ᾽ ὀπίσσω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 7.326; ὀπίσω πάλιν οἴκαδε 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 3.62; ἂψ ὀ. 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 25.74; ἀπίκοντο ὀ. 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.62; ὀ. πορευόμενοι [prev. work] 75; ὀ. ἀναπλῶσαι [prev. work] 78 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἐν τῇ ὀ. κομιδῇ on his way <b>back,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 8.120, compare 1.111, etc. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.3</b></Level3> <b>back again, again,</b> of action that reverses an action or occurrence, ἀνακτᾶσθαι ὀ. τὴν τυραννίδα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 61, compare 68, 2.14; ἀποδόντες ὀ. [prev. author] 5.92.γ᾽ \">Refs</a>]; σφραγίζεις λύεις τ᾽ ὀπίσω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Iphigenia Aulidensis” 38 (_anapaest meter_). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.4</b></Level3> with <i>genitive</i>, δεῦτε ὀ. μου come <b>after</b> me, follow me, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.Matt.4.19. \">NT</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> of Time, <b>hereafter,</b> since the future is unseen and was therefore regarded as <b>behind</b> us, whereas the past is known and therefore before our eyes, ἡμῖν τεκέεσσί τ᾽ ὀπίσσω πῆμα λίποιτο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3.160 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; Τρῳαὶ δέ μ᾽ ὀπίσσω πᾶσαι μωμήσονται[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 411, compare 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 741, “Th.” 488; ἔς περ ὀπίσσω 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 20.199 (εἰσοπίσω 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 1104 (Lyric poetry)); opposed to to νῦν, τούτῳ δ᾽ οὔτ᾽ ἂρ νῦν φρένες ἔμπεδοι [εἰσίν], οὔτ᾽ ἄρ᾽ ὀπίσσω ἔσσονται 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 6.352; to προπάροιθε, σεῖο δ᾽, Ἀχιλλεῦ, οὔ τις ἀνὴρ προπάροιθε [ἦν] μακάρτατος, οὔτ᾽ ἄρ᾽ ὀπίσσω [ἔσσεται] 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.483 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; where ὀπίσσω and πρόσσω are opposed, πρόσσω must be the past and ὀπίσσω the <b>future,</b> οἶδε νοῆσαι ἅμα πρόσσω καὶ ὀπίσσω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.343; ἅμα πρόσσω καὶ ὀ. λεύσσει 3.109; ὅρα πρόσσω καὶ ὀ. 18.250, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 24.452; so ὅσα τ᾽ ἦν ὅσα τ᾽ ἔσθ᾽ ὅσα τ᾽ ἔσται ὀπίσσω 5th c.BC: Empedocles Poeta Philosophus 21.9 (cited in 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Metaphysica” 1000a30)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; οὔτ᾽ ἐνθάδ᾽ ὁρῶν οὔτ᾽ ὀπίσω neither present nor <b>future,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 488 (Lyric poetry); τοὐπίσω σκοπεῖν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Fragmenta” 49; θνητὸς πεφυκὼς τοὐπίσω πειρῶ βλέπειν Isidorus Tragicus 2; compare ὄπισθεν 11.1. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> ἐν τοῖσι ὀ. λόγοις in the books <b>yet to come,</b> in the <b>following</b> books, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.75; compare ὄπισθεν 11.2. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G3694","accentedUnicode":"ὀπίσω","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G3693","matchingForm":"ὄπισθεν","stepTransliteration":"opisthen","gloss":"after","_zh_tw_Gloss":"背後, 跟隨, 後","_es_Gloss":"detrás de","_zh_Gloss":"背后, 跟随, 后"}],"shortDef":"behind, after, following","mediumDef":"behind, after, following <br />can function as an <i>improper preposition</i>, <b>behind, after, at one's back,</b> <ref='Mat.4.10'>Mt. 4:10</ref>; <ref='Luk.7.38'>Lk. 7:38</ref>; <ref='Rev.1.10'>Rev. 1:10;</ref> <greek>τὰ ὀπισω</greek>, <b>the things which are behind,</b> <ref='Php.3.13'>Phil. 3:13;</ref> <greek>ὀπισω</greek> and <greek>εἰς τὰ ὀπισω</greek>, <b>back, backwards,</b> <ref='Mat.24.18'>Mt. 24:18</ref>; <ref='Mrk.13.16'>Mk. 13:16</ref>; <ref='Luk.9.62'>Lk. 9:62</ref>, when an <i>improper preposition</i>, takes the <i>genitive</i>","stepGloss":"after","stepTransliteration":"opisō","count":37,"_es_Definition":"atrás, detrás, hacia atrás, después ","_zh_tw_Definition":"1) (位置) 後面, 背後<br>2) (順序) 之後, 以後<br> 2a) 位置上的<br> 2b) 時間上的","_zh_Definition":"1) (位置) 后面, 背后<br>2) (顺序) 之后, 以后<br> 2a) 位置上的<br> 2b) 时间上的","_step_Type"